---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';

const allCases = await getCollection('cases', ({ data }) => data.published === true);
const allLocations = await getCollection('locations');
const allEvents = await getCollection('events');
const allPeople = await getCollection('people');
const publishedCount = allCases.length;
---

<Base title="Home">
  <div class="hero">
    <h1>Sackar Atlas</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">
      Making the Sackar Inquiry navigable — the people, places, and institutions
      behind thirty hate crime deaths in Sydney.
    </p>
  </div>

  <wa-divider></wa-divider>

  <div class="about">
    <p>
      Between 1970 and 2010, dozens of gay and transgender people were killed in and around
      Sydney in what are now recognised as hate crime deaths. Many were dismissed at the time —
      by police, by courts, by the press — as accidents, suicides, or robberies gone wrong.
    </p>
    <p>
      In December 2023, Justice John Sackar delivered a landmark report documenting 30 of these
      deaths. The report is thorough, careful, and important. It is also a government document:
      dense, formal, and structured in a way that makes its connections invisible. Two men fell
      from the same cliff in Manly thirteen months apart. The same Strike Force confused two
      hotels and never noticed. A PDF can document these facts. It cannot show you what they
      mean together.
    </p>
    <p>
      Sackar Atlas takes that public record and makes those connections visible. Real people,
      named and placed in the city where they lived and died. Real places — the beats, the
      venues, the police jurisdictions — where a pattern becomes clear. Real institutions whose
      failures, seen together, tell a story that no individual case file can. This is Sydney’s
      history. This is what happened.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>This is a live research project.</strong> Records are added and corrected as
      research progresses. Every case is verified against primary sources.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="home-nav">
    <a href="/cases/" class="nav-card">
      <span class="nav-card-label">Cases</span>
      <span class="nav-card-count">{publishedCount} published</span>
      <span class="nav-card-desc">Individual records for each person examined by the Inquiry</span>
    </a>
    <a href="/locations/" class="nav-card">
      <span class="nav-card-label">Locations</span>
      <span class="nav-card-count">{allLocations.length} places</span>
      <span class="nav-card-desc">Beats, nightlife venues, crime scenes, and police jurisdictions</span>
    </a>
    <a href="/events/" class="nav-card">
      <span class="nav-card-label">Events</span>
      <span class="nav-card-count">{allEvents.length} events</span>
      <span class="nav-card-desc">Activism, law reform, cultural moments, and police actions</span>
    </a>
    <a href="/people/" class="nav-card">
      <span class="nav-card-label">People</span>
      <span class="nav-card-count">{allPeople.length} people</span>
      <span class="nav-card-desc">Victims, activists, police, legal figures, and political actors</span>
    </a>
    <a href="/map/" class="nav-card">
      <span class="nav-card-label">Map</span>
      <span class="nav-card-count">Sydney &amp; surrounds</span>
      <span class="nav-card-desc">Death sites, known beats, venues, and police jurisdictions</span>
    </a>
  </div>

  <wa-divider></wa-divider>

  <div class="source-note">
    <h2 class="mt-0">Source and methodology</h2>
    <p>
      All records are drawn from public documents:
    </p> 
    <li>the SCOI report volumes</li>
    <li>public NSW government data</li>
    <li>Trove archives</li>
    <li>NSW police annual reports. </li>

    <p>AI tools are used to synthesise and structure data from these sources, making them more accessible
      to the general public.</p>

    <p>Every claim links to a primary source. Referencing follows the
      <a href="https://www.stylemanual.gov.au/referencing-and-attribution/author-date">Australian Government Style Manual</a>
      (author–date system).
    </p>
    <p>
      Data is published under
      <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/">CC-BY 4.0</a>.
      Journalism is copyright Anna Roberts. Code is MIT.
      See <a href="https://github.com/bitsloppy/sackar-atlas/blob/main/LICENSING.md">LICENSING.md</a>
      for the full licence map.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  .hero {
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .hero h1 {
    font-size: 2.6rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .subtitle {
    font-family: var(--font-ui);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    max-width: 60ch;
    line-height: 1.5;
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .about {
    margin: 2rem 0;
    max-width: 70ch;
  }

  .home-nav {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(220px, 1fr));
    gap: 1rem;
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .nav-card {
    background: var(--surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 1.5rem;
    text-decoration: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.3rem;
    transition: border-color 0.15s;
  }
  .nav-card:hover { border-color: var(--accent); }

  .nav-card-label {
    font-family: var(--font-ui);
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--nav-bg);
  }

  .nav-card-count {
    font-family: var(--font-ui);
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .nav-card-desc {
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    color: var(--text);
    margin-top: 0.25rem;
    line-height: 1.4;
  }

  .source-note {
    margin-top: 2rem;
  }

  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2rem; }
    .home-nav { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
  }
</style>
